In TypeScript, you can use the `interface` keyword along with the `Object` type to express that an object may have multiple types but in practice, it will only have a specific type. This is often referred to as an "optional type" or "default type". Here is an example:

```typescript
type MyObject<T> = {
  name: string | { type: string; value: number } | null;
  age: number | { age: number; year: number };
};

// Usage
const myObject: MyObject<number|string> = { name: "Alice", age: 30 };

console.log(myObject.name); // string
console.log(myObject.age); // number
console.log(myObject.type); // string | number
```

In this example, `MyObject` can be of type `string`, `{ type: string; value: number }`, or `null`. In practice, you know that the value will be either a `string` or a `number`. The `null` type is included as a potential type but is not enforced to be used.

If you want to enforce that the type must be either `string`, `number`, or `null`, you can use the `Option` type from the `typing` module:

```typescript
import { Option } from 'typing';

type MyObject<T> = {
  name: string | { type: string; value: number } | null;
  age: number | { age: number; year: number };
};

interface RequiredType {
  type: T;
  value?: T;
}

const requiredObject: MyObject<RequiredType> = {
  name: "Alice",
  age: 30,
};

console.log(requiredObject.name); // string
console.log(requiredObject.age); // number
console.log(requiredObject.type); // string
```

In this version, `MyObject` can only be assigned to `RequiredType` instances, ensuring that the type is either `string`, `number`, or `null`. The `Option` type is used to represent the optional nature of the object's types.

